Nutritional ketosis or simply ketosis is a  normally  taking place metabolic state where your body  makes use of ketones (fat) for  gas  as opposed to  sugar ( carbs).


It  occurs when the body burns up all its  carb stores. Or,  when it comes to ketogenic diet, the  carb  consumption is  really low. In both of these cases, the liver  transforms dietary fats and  fat into a fatty acid called ketone.



 Exactly How Ketosis Burns Fat


Insulin levels drop  throughout ketosis,  therefore releasing fats from your fat cells. As fats  load your liver,  most of it  ultimately  becomes ketones.


Your body will then be able to  utilize these ketones as a  gas  resource.  Usually, if the body  requires energy, it would always prioritize  carbs.   Nonetheless, if no  carbohydrates are present, it would burn ketones instead.

A note on 'Ivan the Terrible' - in Russia, Ivan IV has the epithet 'Гро́зный' meaning 'Great' or 'Formidable'. So why is he known as Ivan 'the Terrible' in English? Because he was evil or useless or because of anti-Russian bias? No, because 'Terrible' in English also means awesome or formidable - this was well understood when 'Гро́зный' was first translated into English centuries ago, but now fewer people understand this. (see definitions 3 & 4 here: http://www.dictionary.com/browse/terr...). The name stuck, and Ivan IV has been known as Ivan the Terrible ever since.

description:
There are worries that the UK will be pressured into accepting chlorinated chicken as part of a UK-US trade deal.

But what is chlorinated chicken? And why is it seen as a problem?

Chlorinated chicken is poultry meat that has been washed with chlorine.

After slaughter, the chickens are rinsed with an antimicrobial chlorine wash to protect consumers from food-borne diseases.

This is done to treat high levels of bacteria, a symptom of poor hygiene and low animal welfare conditions not allowed in UK farming.

The practice of chlorine washing chicken is banned in the UK, but it is common practice in the US poultry industry.

Discover everything you need to know about chlorinated chicken below.

For more information see the Soil Association at

https://www.soilassociation.org/cause...
